{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1395"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1395"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.08,0.34,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62227"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1270"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is an in-patient in the orthopaedic unit for a total hip replacement following a fall. Five days after his surgery, he presents with an acute onset of dyspnoea and cough while lying on his bed at night. He complains of left-sided pleuritic chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has tachypnoea and tachycardia. There are no abnormal findings on lung examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile waiting for diagnostic investigations, the night intern organises an arterial blood gas (ABG).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would you expect to find on this individual\u0027s arterial blood gas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypoxaemia, hypocapnia, alkalosis","Hypoxaemia, hypocapnia, acidosis","Hypoxaemia, hypercapnia, acidosis","Hypoxaemia, normal PaCO2, normal pH","Normal PaO2, hypercapnia, acidosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with pulmonary embolism, a known complication of major orthopaedic surgery and the immobility associated with the recovery period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory alkalosis develops when the lungs are stimulated to remove CO2 that is produced metabolically in the tissues. The increase in alveolar ventilation in pulmonary embolism leads to a decrease in PaCO2 (\u003Cstrong\u003Ehypocapnia\u003C/strong\u003E) and an increase in the blood pH. This hyperventilation is a response to hypoxaemia and the body\u0027s attempt to maintain adequate oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMismatch of ventilation and perfusion is a common cause of impaired pulmonary oxygen transfer during an acute pulmonary embolism. Ventilation in normal lungs is well matched to blood flow. However, during an acute pulmonary embolism, the emboli cause a redistribution of blood flow. This means that some areas of the lung have a lower ventilation to perfusion ratio whilst other areas have an excessively higher ventilation to perfusion ratio. When venous blood flow enters lung areas with low ventilation to capillary blood flow, this results in arterial \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoxaemia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is unusual for pulmonary embolism to present as respiratory acidosis with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypercapnia\u003C/strong\u003E unless shock is present. This investigation is neither specific nor diagnostic: pulmonary embolism may also present as a normal ABG.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary embolism often presents with hypoxaemia, hypocapnia, and respiratory alkalosis on arterial blood gas."],"references":["Rodger MA, Carrier M, Jones GN, et al. Diagnostic value of arterial blood gas measurement in suspected pulmonary embolism. Am J Respir Crit Care Med 2000; 162:2105.","Sarkar M, Niranjan N, Banyal PK. Mechanisms of hypoxemia. Lung India. 2017 Jan-Feb;34(1):47-60. doi: 10.4103/0970-2113.197116. Erratum in: Lung India. 2017 Mar-Apr;34(2):220. doi: 10.4103/0970-2113.201292. PMID: 28144061; PMCID: PMC5234199.","Stein PD, Goldhaber SZ, Henry JW. Alveolar-arterial oxygen gradient in the assessment of acute pulmonary embolism. Chest. 1995 Jan;107(1):139-43. doi: 10.1378/chest.107.1.139. PMID: 7632205.","Goldhaber SZ, Elliott CG. Acute pulmonary embolism: part I: epidemiology, pathophysiology, and diagnosis. Circulation. 2003 Dec 2;108(22):2726-9. doi: 10.1161/01.CIR.0000097829.89204.0C. PMID: 14656907."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1395"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62227"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T19:33:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T19:33:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1395"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76734"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou